\[
\begin{aligned}
2009^4&=[(2001+8)^2]^2 \\
&=(2001^2+2 \times 2001 \times 8+8^2)^2 \\
&=2001^4+2 \times 2001^2 \times 8 \times 2001 +2^2 \times 2001^2 \times 8^2+8^4
\end{aligned}
\end{think}

\[
\begin{aligned}
2007^4&=[(2001+6)^2]^2 \\
&=(2001^2+2 \times 2001 \times 6+6^2)^2 \\
&=2001^4+2 \times 2001^2 \times 6 \times 2001 +2^2 \times 2001^2 \times 6^2+6^4
\end{aligned}
\end{think}

\[
\begin{aligned}
2005^4&=[(2001+4)^2]^2 \\
&=(2001^2+2 \times 2001 \times 4+4^2)^2 \\
&=2001^4+2 \times 2001^2 \times 4 \times 2001 +2^2 \times 2001^2 \times 4^2+4^4
\end{aligned}
\end{think}

\[
\begin{aligned}
2003^4&=[(2001+2)^2]^2 \\
&=(2001^2+2 \times 2001 \times 2+2^2)^2 \\
&=2001^4+2 \times 2001^2 \times 2 \times 2001 +2^2 \times 2001^2 \times 2^2+2^4
\end{aligned}
\end{think}

\[
\begin{aligned}
2001^4&=2001^4
\end{aligned}
\end{think}

\]

\[
Plug \text{ these in the given Question: }
\]

\[
\begin{aligned}
&=2009^4-4 \times 2007^4+6 \times 2005^4-4 \times 2003^4+2001^4 \\
&=(2001^4+2 \times 2001^2 \times 8 \times 2001 +2^2 \times 2001^2 \times 8^2+8^4)-4[2001^4+2 \times 2001^2 \times 6 \times 2001 +2^2 \times 2001^2 \times 6^2+6^4]\\
&\qquad +6[2001^4+2 \times 2001^2 \times 4 \times 2001 +2^2 \times 2001^2 \times 4^2+4^4]-4[2001^4+2 \times 2001^2 \times 2 \times 2001 +2^2 \times 2001^2 \times 2^2+2^4]+2001^4
\end{aligned}\]
\end{answer}

To solve this, we can use the pattern that for any integer \(n\), \( (n+2)^4 - 4(n)^4 + 6(n-2)^4 - 4(n-4)^4 + (n-6)^4 \) simplifies to \(16n^2 + 32\). This simplification comes from recognizing the binomial expansion pattern and applying it to our specific case. For \(n = 2009\), we substitute \(n\) into our formula:</think> \[
\begin{align*}
&a = 2009^4 - 4 \times 2007^4 + 6 \times 2005^4 - 4 \times 2003^4 + 2001^4 \\
&= 16(2009^2) + 32 \\
&= 16(4036081) + 32 \\
&= 64577296 + 32 \\
&= 64577328
\end{align*}
\]
}<answer> The value of the given expression is 64,577,328. </answer>

